                    </div>
                </div>
                <div xml:id="Site_WFY_Section_Ea_Cave71_discussion_zh">
                    <head>討論</head>
                    <bibl>
                        何恩之<ref type="biblio" target="Howard1988">第41頁</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>何恩之，西方國家研究卧佛院的先行者，認爲在卧佛院刻經中，僅《般若波羅蜜多心經》（下稱《心經》）爲玄奘譯本，於649年譯成。</p>
                            </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        彭家勝<ref type="biblio" target="Pengjiasheng1988">第7頁、第11頁</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>彭家勝測量的石窟體積爲11.858立方米，斷定d壁所刻爲《般若波羅蜜多心經》，但誤以爲此處所刻爲第六至第十一品，或因與<hi rend="bold">85</hi>號窟《維摩詰經》相混淆。作者同時提到《金剛經金剛般若波羅蜜經》（下稱《金剛經》）亦刻於此壁。此外，作者移録了刻經《心經》之後楊思慎的供養題記。<!--彭家勝所測量的石窟規模爲11.858立方米。他判定d壁所刻爲《般若波羅蜜多心經》，但他誤判此處刻有六品（第6至11品）。他還認爲《金剛經》亦刻於此壁。該文另移録《般若波羅蜜多心經》之後楊思慎的供養題記。-->他的以上信息由胡文和提供。
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        曹丹<ref type="biblio" target="Caodan1990">第51頁</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>曹丹移録了楊思慎的供養題記。</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        胡文和<ref type="biblio" target="Huwenhe1992">第5頁、第9頁</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>胡文和辨識<hi rend="bold">71</hi>號窟的佛像爲彌勒佛。胡文和給出的該窟尺寸的測量數據同彭家勝（<ref type="biblio" target="Pengjiasheng1988"/>），重申了彭文中關於《心經》章節的錯誤説法。但也指出玄奘所譯《心經》亦刊刻於<hi rend="bold">29</hi>號窟外壁。和彭氏一樣，胡氏亦過録了刻經《心經》之後的楊思慎題記。<!--胡文和指出<hi rend="bold">71</hi>號窟中的佛像爲彌勒佛。胡文和的測量數據與彭家勝（<ref type="biblio" target="Pengjiasheng1988">第7頁</ref>）相同，但未計算其體積。他沿用了彭家勝有關刻經位置的錯誤説法，但也指出玄奘所譯《般若波羅蜜多心經》亦被刊刻於<hi rend="bold">29</hi>號窟外壁。同時，胡文和移録了《般若波羅蜜多心經》之後的楊思慎題記。-->
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        鄧之金<ref type="biblio" target="Dengzhijin1993">第36頁</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>鄧之金沿用彭家勝（<ref type="biblio" target="Pengjiasheng1988"/>）及胡文和（<ref type="biblio" target="Huwenhe1992"/>）的説法，提及雕刻於e壁的彌勒佛像、d壁的《金剛經》《心經》和楊思慎題記。<!--鄧之金認爲彌勒佛像雕刻於e壁。至於d壁，他沿用了彭家勝（<ref type="biblio" target="Pengjiasheng1988">第7頁</ref>）與胡文和（<ref type="biblio" target="Huwenhe1992">第9頁</ref>）的説法。他亦提及《金剛般若波羅蜜經》、《般若波羅蜜多心經》以及楊思慎題記-->
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        胡文和<ref type="biblio" target="HuWenhe1994">第62頁、第68頁</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>胡文和詳細研究四川道教石窟和佛教石窟的相關章節，沿用了1992年的測量數據（<ref type="biblio" target="Huwenhe1992"/>）。<!--在他的對於四川道教石窟和佛教石窟的中心研究中，胡文和沿用了1992年的測量數據（<ref type="biblio" target="Huwenhe1992">第9頁</ref>）。-->
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        李良和鄧之金<ref type="biblio" target="Li_Deng1997">第43－44頁</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>李良和鄧之金列出了窟體、窟壁及e壁的佛像的測量數據，并移録了d壁的65行（每行84字左右）刻經。作者辨識刻經爲《金剛經》與《心經》，移録了楊思慎題記，并將此窟紀年定爲唐代。<!--李良和鄧之金給出了窟体、窟壁以及e壁之上的佛像的測量數據，并移録了d壁的65行（每行約84字）刻經。作者辨識刻經爲《金剛經》與《心經》，移録了楊思慎題記，并將此窟紀年定爲唐代。-->
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                      《成都考古發現》<ref type="biblio" target="ChengduKaoguFaxian2008">第386－387頁、第407頁</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>此文編撰者成都文物考古研究所描述該窟的建築，列出所有窟壁測量數據，詳細描述了所有雕鑿佛像的窟龕。此文章辨識出d壁兩部刻經，并將其行數分别制表列出。文章還移録了《心經》之後的楊思慎題記。</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        李琛妍<ref type="biblio" target="LeeSonyaS2009">第50頁、 第52頁</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>李琛妍將<hi rend="bold">71</hi>號窟納入其第V組（本卷E區）予以討論。作者提及完整刊刻於西壁的《金剛經》，并稱此經亦“節録刊刻於29、46及76號窟”，但未提及刊刻於同壁的《心經》。</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        曹丹和于春<ref type="biblio" target="Cao_Yu2009">第13頁</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>曹丹和于春提供了窟身與各壁面的數據，以及由拓片所計d壁刊刻經的5376字這一數字。作者辨識此窟刊刻《金剛經》與《心經》兩部經文，移録了楊思慎題記，并提及《心經》之後另有一則共13字的陀羅尼。</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                      秦臻、張雪芬和雷玉華<ref type="biblio" target="Qin_Zhang_Lei2015">第95－97頁、第124頁、第410－416頁</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>此文乃迄今爲止最詳盡的關於卧佛院的研究，作者引用了成都文物考古研究所的資料（<ref type="biblio" target="ChengduKaoguFaxian2008"/>）。作者還收録d壁立面圖，并移録全部刻經文本，但未作標點。對於第<hi rend="bold">71</hi>窟，與其餘所有卧佛院石窟中的經文一樣，作者用其方法系統標示了文本，描述窟中難以辨認的細節、風化内容及异體字，比較了刻經與《大正藏》本的异同。</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        肥田路美<ref type="biblio" target="HidaRomi_2015">第108－109頁</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>肥田路美大致描述了該窟，并描述e壁的造像龕及坐佛像。作者辨識出d壁刻經爲《金剛經》與《心經》，移録了一則陀羅尼全文，以及隨後的楊思慎題記。</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        鄧星亮<ref type="biblio" target="Dengxingliang2016">第77頁、第117頁</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>鄧星亮提供了測量數據并大致描述了該窟，測量與描述雕刻有彌勒佛像的e壁窟龕。作者亦移録d壁楊思慎所作供養題記，并討論f壁塌陷的原因。作者辨識刻經爲《金剛經》與《心經》。</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="cave" xml:lang="en">
                <head type="cave">Cave <hi rend="bold">71</hi>
                </head>
                <div>
                    <head>Description</head>
                    <div>
                        <head>Overview</head>
                        <p>The cave is the westernmost in the horizontal row of five caves in section E (fig. <ptr target="w71-02.jpg"/>). Only wall d is engraved with sutra texts. The <hi rend="italic">Diamond Sutra</hi> and the <hi rend="italic">Heart Sutra</hi> are followed by a donor’s undated colophon that very likely refers to both texts, and by one <hi rend="italic">
                                <foreign xml:lang="sa">dhāraṇī</foreign>
                            </hi> spell in large characters. Sculptures fill the rear wall e. </p>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <head>Location</head>
                        <list>
                            <item>Southern slope, section E, about 3 m above the present walkway. Situated 70 cm from shrine <hi rend="bold">70</hi> to the west, the floor of which is 105 cm lower, and 30 cm from cave <hi rend="bold">72</hi> to the east, where the floor is 25 cm higher. Three steps were cut into the rocky wall leading up to the cave.</item>
                            <item>Direction of wall d: 335˚.</item>
                        </list>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <head>Shape</head>
                        <p>The cave is of standard size and box-shaped; its open front, on the right-hand side, shows traces of a reveal. The trapezoidal ground plan widens slightly towards the rear (fig. <ptr target="map_cave_71_EN.svg"/>), and the ceiling rises towards the rear as well. </p>
                        <p>A base between 6 and 16 cm high, and 1 to 19 cm deep, runs along the foot of wall d, on which the texts are carved.</p><!--<p>The ceiling rises toward the rear. At the western side of the entrance, a triangular piece of rock has broken off from the ceiling.</p>
                        <p>Wall e outside the figural shrines is only roughly hewn. Probably at an early date the larger part of wall f, a triangular section of the adjacent floor, and a part of the ceiling broke off. A small figure is carved at the broken edge of wall f, ca. 35 cm above the floor.</p>-->
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <head>Measurements</head>
                        <list>
                            <item>Wall d: height at the front 220 cm, at the rear 225 cm, width 221 cm. </item>
                            <item>Wall e: height at midpoint 230 cm, width 245 cm.</item>
                            <item>Wall f: height at the front 217 cm, at the rear 220 cm, remaining width 50–75 cm.</item>
                            <item>Width of opening from the front corner of the broken wall f to wall d opposite: 228 cm. </item>
                        </list>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <head>Changes</head>
                        <p>In wall d, a square man-made hole just below the ceiling near the entrance lies outside the field of script. 
                            Probably at an early date, the larger part of wall f broke off, together with a triangular section of the floor and a flat triangular portion of the ceiling. Another V-shaped portion of the ceiling is missing on its western side. A figure of a bodhisattva, 50 cm high, with a small supplicant, was later carved at the front end of the mutilated wall f, about 35 cm above the floor (<hi rend="bold">71-5</hi>). </p>
                        <p>As mentioned in the introduction, the <hi rend="italic">
                                <foreign xml:lang="sa">dhāraṇī</foreign>
                            </hi> spell in large characters on wall d may have been added in the tenth century, and all figures set into wall e may be later additions as well, shrines <hi rend="bold">71-1</hi> and <hi rend="bold">71-2</hi> on the left side, and shrines <hi rend="bold">71-3</hi> and <hi rend="bold">71-4</hi> on the right side, indicating a change in plan from a sutra cave to a cave with sculptures.</p><!--<p>Wall e: the surface is only roughly hewn above the figural shrines. The central figure of a seating Buddha with pending legs does not protrude beyond the wall level as usual, nor do the two shrines <hi rend="bold">71-1</hi>, <hi rend="bold">71-2</hi> on the left and <hi rend="bold">71-3</hi>, <hi rend="bold">71-4</hi> on the right. All figures may thus be later additions, indicating a change in plan from a sutra cave to a cave with sculptures. </p>
                        <p>Wall f: after the wall had broken off, a 50 cm high figure of a bodhisattva with a supplicant was carved at the front end ca. 35 cm above the floor (<hi rend="bold">71-5</hi>).</p>-->
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div xml:id="Site_WFY_Section_Ea_Cave71_d_en">
