                <div xml:id="Site_WFY_Section_Ea_Cave71_discussion_en">
                    <head>Discussion</head>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="Howard1988">41</ref>
                        <note>Howard, who pioneered the study of the Grove in the West, says that Xuanzang’s translations are only represented at the Grove by the carving of the <hi rend="italic">Heart of the Perfection of Wisdom Sutra </hi>
                            <foreign xml:lang="zh">般若波羅蜜多心經</foreign>, which was translated in 649.</note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="Pengjiasheng1988">7, 11</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>Peng gives measurements of the cave and computes its volume as 11.858 cubic meters. He identifies the text carved on wall d as the <hi rend="italic">Heart of the Perfection of Wisdom Sutra</hi>, yet erroneously says that the engraving consists of chapters 6–11, perhaps confusing it with the <hi rend="italic">
                                    <foreign xml:lang="sa">Vimalakīrti</foreign> Sutra</hi> in cave <hi rend="bold">85</hi>. He also mentions the <hi rend="italic">Diamond Sutra</hi> carved on the same wall. In addition, he transcribes the colophon by Yang Sishen <foreign xml:lang="zh">楊思慎</foreign> that follows after the <hi rend="italic">Heart Sutra</hi>. He was given this information by Hu Wenhe.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="Caodan1990">51</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>Cao gives a transcription of the colophon by Yang Sishen. </p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="Huwenhe1992">5, 9</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>Hu Wenhe identifies the Buddha figure in cave <hi rend="bold">71</hi> as Maitreya. He gives the same dimensions of the cave as published in <ref type="biblio" target="Pengjiasheng1988"/>. He repeats the error concerning the <hi rend="italic">Heart Sutra</hi>’s chapters, but points out that the same translation of the sutra, by Xuanzang, was also carved outside cave <hi rend="bold">29</hi>. He transcribes Yang Sishen’s colophon that follows the <hi rend="italic">Heart Sutra</hi> as published before in <ref type="biblio" target="Pengjiasheng1988"/>.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="Dengzhijin1993">36</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>Following <ref type="biblio" target="Pengjiasheng1988"/> and <ref type="biblio" target="Huwenhe1992"/>, Deng Zhijin mentions a Maitreya figure carved on wall e, and the <hi rend="italic">Diamond Sutra </hi> and the <hi rend="italic">Heart Sutra </hi> on wall d, as well as the colophon by Yang Sishen.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="HuWenhe1994">62, 68</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>In the relevant section in his comprehensive study of Daoist and Buddhist caves in Sichuan, Hu Wenhe repeats the information given in his earlier publication, <ref type="biblio" target="Huwenhe1992"/>.
                                
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="Li_Deng1997">43–44</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>The authors give measurements for the cave, the walls, and the Buddha statue on wall e. They list 65 text columns on wall d with an average of 84 characters per column. They identify the sutras as the <hi rend="italic">Diamond Sutra </hi> and the <hi rend="italic">Heart of the Perfection of Wisdom Sutra</hi>, and quote the colophon by Yang Sishen. They date the cave to the Tang period.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="ChengduKaoguFaxian2008">386–387, 407</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>The editors of the Chengdu Municipal Institute of Cultural Relics and Archaeology provide descriptions of the architecture of the cave, including measurements of all the walls. All the niches with sculptures are described in great detail. The editors identify both sutras carved on wall d, and tabulate the column numbers for each sutra. They also transcribe the colophon by Yang Sishen following the <hi rend="italic">Heart of the Perfection of Wisdom Sutra</hi>.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="LeeSonyaS2009">50, 52</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>Lee includes cave <hi rend="bold">71</hi> in her cluster V, which corresponds to section E. She mentions the <hi rend="italic">Diamond Sutra</hi>, which was engraved in its entirety on the west wall. She maintains that this sutra was also carved “in a variety of excerpted forms in caves <hi rend="bold">29</hi>, <hi rend="bold">46</hi>, and <hi rend="bold">76</hi>.” She does not mention the <hi rend="italic">Heart Sutra</hi> carved on the same wall.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="Cao_Yu2009">13</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>Cao and Yu provide measurements of the walls, their surface areas, and, based on rubbings, the number of extant characters on wall d: 5376. They identify both of the sutras carved in this cave, the <hi rend="italic">Diamond Sutra</hi> and the <hi rend="italic">Heart Sutra</hi>. They transcribe the colophon by Yang Sishen and mention the thirteen large characters of the spell.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="Qin_Zhang_Lei2015">95–97, 124, 410–416</ref>
                        <note>
                          <p>In this most comprehensive study of the Grove to date, the authors repeat the information given in <ref type="biblio" target="ChengduKaoguFaxian2008"/>. They include a diagram of wall d, as well as a full transcription without punctuation. For cave <hi rend="bold">71</hi>, as for all the other sutra caves at the Grove, they analyze the text systematically, with their own scheme, detailing illegible and worn characters, variant characters (<hi rend="italic">yiti zi </hi>
                                <foreign xml:lang="zh">异體字</foreign>), and differences with the <hi rend="italic">
                                    <foreign xml:lang="ja">Taishō</foreign>
                                </hi> edition.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="HidaRomi_2015">108–109</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>Hida provides a general description of the cave, and a description of the niches on wall e, including the large Buddha statue seated with legs pendants. She identifies the <hi rend="italic">Diamond Sutra</hi> and the <hi rend="italic">Heart Sutra</hi> that were carved on wall d, and she gives a full transcription of the <hi rend="italic">
                                    <foreign xml:lang="sa">dhāraṇī</foreign>
                                </hi> spell, as well as of the colophon by Yang Sishen that follow the sutra texts.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="Dengxingliang2016">77, 117</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>Deng Xingliang provides measurements and a general description of the cave, as well as measurements and a description of the niches on wall e, including the large Maitreya statue. He transcribes the votive inscription by Yang Sishen on wall d, and speculates on the reasons why wall f collapsed. He identifies the <hi rend="italic">Diamond Sutra</hi> and the <hi rend="italic">Heart Sutra</hi> carved on wall d.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                </div>
            </div>
